Type Conversions in C
Type conversion refers to converting a variable from one data type to another. In C, this happens in two ways: Implicit and Explicit.

Implicit Type Conversion (Automatic)

This conversion is handled automatically by the compiler without user intervention.

For example, declaring int a = 10; automatically directs the compiler to interpret and store the literal value as an integer type.

Similarly, if you assign a floating-point variable to an integer variable (e.g., int b = a; where a is 10.99), the compiler implicitly handles the data transfer. However, it truncates the fractional part (.99) and saves only the whole integer portion (10) to memory.

Explicit Type Conversion (Type Casting)

This conversion is explicitly performed by the programmer using a casting operator.

Syntax: Place the target data type inside parentheses directly before the variable to be converted: (target_type) variable;

Example:

C
float a = 10.99;
int b = (int)a; // Explicitly casts the float 'a' into an integer before assignin
